The '''Camden Shipyard & Maritime Museum''' is a [[maritime museum]] in the [[Waterfront South]] neighborhood of [[Camden, New Jersey]], across the [[Delaware River]] from [[Philadelphia]].

The museum opened in September 2016.<ref>Carol Comegno, [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/local/south-jersey/2016/09/11/camden-shipyard-museum-opens-raves/90240270/ Camden shipyard museum opens to raves], ''USA Today'' (September 11, 2016).</ref> Its main building is the former Church of our Savior, and its grounds include land once owned by the [[New York Shipbuilding Corporation|New York Shipbuilding Co.]], which is said to have been, at one time, the largest shipbuilder in the world.<ref name="GenoveseBuildingHope">{{cite news|last1=Genovese|first1=Peter|title=Hope floats: In nation's most dangerous city, Camden kids build boats, trust, confidence|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2014/02/hope_floats_in_nations_most_dangerous_city.html|accessdate=18 July 2016|newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=28 February 2014}}</ref><ref name="Riordan">{{cite news|last1=Riordan|first1=Kevin|title=In Camden, new museum to enshrine city's maritime history|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/local/20160717_In_Camden__new_museum_to_enshrine_city_s_maritime_history.html|accessdate=18 July 2016|newspaper=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=17 July 2016}}</ref>

