{{About|the Roman goddess|other uses|Decima (disambiguation){{!}}Decima}}
{{refimprove|date=May 2013}}
In [[Roman mythology]], '''Decima''' was one of the three [[Parcae]], or often known in English as the [[Moirae|Fates]]. [[Nona (deity)|Nona]] and Decima were responsible for birth, while [[Morta]] was charged with overseeing death. They distributed to mankind all the good and bad things in life, and even [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] had to bend to their will.  She measured the thread of life with her rod, like her Greek equivalent [[Lachesis (mythology)|Lachesis]]. Her mother is the goddess of night and her father is the god of darkness.

