The '''National Gallery and Tate Gallery Act 1954''' is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] (2 & 3 Eliz II c. 65). The Act came into force in 1955 and created a legal separation between the [[National Gallery, London|National Gallery]] and the [[Tate Gallery]] and established the Tate as an independent institution. 

The Act was repealed on 1 September 1992 by the [[Museums and Galleries Act 1992]], which created a board of trustees to operate the Tate.

