{{Infobox person | name = Winthrop Kellogg Edey | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1938 | birth_place = Upper Brookville, New York | death_date = 1999 (Age 61) | death_place = New York City | nationality = American | other_names = | occupation = Collector, scholar | years_active = 1960-1999 | known_for = Scholarship of clocks | notable_works = | religion = }} '''Winthrop Kellogg "Kelly" Edey''' (1938–1999) was a noted collector and [[Horology|horologist]] who lived in [[Manhattan]], New York City. His collection of timepieces is now in the [[Frick Collection]]. He also makes appearances in Andy Warhol's ''Screen Tests''.
==Life and career== Through his mother's family, Kelly was an heir of [[KBR (company)#M. W. Kellogg|Morris W. Kellogg]], founder of a major engineering company.<ref name="NYT-obit">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/28/nyregion/winthrop-k-edey-61-clock-enthusiast-dies.html|title=Winthrop K. Edey, 61, Clock Enthusiast, Dies|last1=Thomas|first1=Robert McG Jr.|date=28 February 1999|work=The New York Times}}</ref> He grew up in [[Upper Brookville]], [[Long Island]] and graduated from Amherst College.<ref name="NYT-obit" /> His father, Maitland Edey, was an author and editor of [[Time Life#Book series|Time-Life Books]]; his mother, Nancy Winthrop Edey was a psychiatrist and activist in the field of women's reproductive rights.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pace|first1=Eric|title=Dr. Helen Winthrop Edey, 86, Philanthropist and Psychiatrist|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/09/29/nyregion/dr-helen-winthrop-edey-86-philanthropist-and-psychiatrist.html|work=New York Times|issue=29 September 1998}}</ref>
Over five decades, beginning when he was a boy, Edey assembled a significant collection of clocks, watches and associated research materials that he donated to the Frick after his death. He was a noted scholar of timepieces, and executed repairs on his collection himself.<ref name=NYT-obit /> Edy wrote the catalogue to the 1982 Frick exhibition ''French Clocks in North American Collections''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Edey|first1=Winthrop|title=French Clocks in North American Collections|date=1982|publisher=Frick Collection|location=New York|isbn=9780912114118|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/French_Clocks_in_North_American_Collecti.html?id=rLWzQwAACAAJ}}</ref> His bequest to the Frick includes 39 timepieces, including [[André Charles Boulle]]'s famed [[Barometer Clock (Boulle)|Barometer Clock]], together with his library of horological and other materials.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Andrewes|first1=William J.H.|title=The Art Of the Timekeeper: Masterpieces from the Winthrop Edey Bequest (exh. cat.)|date=2001|publisher=The Frick Collection|location=New York|isbn=9780912114194}}</ref> Edey also collected and conducted research in other areas, notably Egyptology and Classical literature.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reist|first1=Inge|title=Kelly Edey: In LIfe and In Memoriam, exhibition brochure|date=2001|publisher=Frick Art Reference Library|url=https://www.frick.org/sites/default/files/pdf/library/Edey_Brochure.pdf}}</ref> He gave several works to the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] when he died, including sculptures by [[Augustus Saint-Gaudens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Winthrop Edey bequest search|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection#!?q=bequest%20of%20winthrop%20edey|website=Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref>
Edey was gay<ref>{{cite book|last1=Morrisroe|first1=Patricia|title=Mapplethorpe : A Biography|date=1995|publisher=Random House|location=New York|isbn=9780394576503|pages=236; 242; 293|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=La3bAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> and part of New York City's cultural and artistic life; he was friendly [[Robert Mapplethorpe]] and [[Andy Warhol]], among others. Warhol's first ''[[Screen Tests]]'' were likely filmed at Edey's townhouse on West 83rd Street, Manhattan. Edey himself appears in several ''Screen Tests'', as well as some versions of the ''Screen Test'' compilation, ''Thirteen Most Beautiful Boys''.<ref>{{cite book|title=Andy Warhol Screen Tests|last1=Angell|first1=Callie|date=2006|publisher=Harry N. Abrams|isbn=9780810955394|location=New York|pages=42; 70}}</ref> He kept a diary that extensively documents his life in New York City and elsewhere over several decades, which has been described as "Proustian in its sweep and attention to detail."<ref name="NYT-obit" /> The diary is in the collection of the Frick but is not available to the public.
